put (one) in crook with
Homonym Number:
Word Class:phrase
Sense Number:
Definition:to put someone in bad with, to reduce one's standing in the eyes of someone else, also be in crook with.
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes: ca1930 (Harold Griffiths, p.c. Dec 12, 1959) `You wouldn't put me crook with him, would you?'
Citations
